as a colossally tragic or colossally generative event, but also because the social, cultural, scientific, and even moral residues of the revolution remain everywhere in Putin’s Russia. Revolutionary Aftereffects looks at the ways in which 1917 has and continues to be commemorated in Russia. Although post-Soviet Russia has emphasized its complete break with the past, this study of the memorialization and legacy of 1917 explores a fundamental continuity underlying an apparent discourse of discontinuity in post-socialist Russia. Contributors provide insight into the continuing reverberations of the revolution from a variety of disciplinary perspectives, not just history and literary studies but also heritage studies, anthropology, geography, and sociology. Collectively, they demonstrate the changing nature of the revolution’s memorialization in the Soviet Union and post-Soviet Russia and the ambivalence and contradictions within those narratives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  a1917 revolution.  aBoris Akunin.  aLenin.  aRussian Revolution.  aRussian architecture.  aSilent Jubilee.  aSoviet Union.  aVladimir Putin.  aanniversaries.  acentenary.  amemorialization of the past.  apost-socialist Russia.1 aAnderson, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaraban, Elena V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeschepper, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipovetsky, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilina, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwift, Megan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwift, Megan, eeditor.4edt4http://id